properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: The Danish motor ship suffered a severe fire while at anchor near Tongue Point, killing 11 people aboard.
Stranded on Peacock Spit while entering the Columbia River. The vessel and its party were miraculously saved.
Wrecked off Clatsop Spit in May 1944, with the loss of two crew members.
Wrecked on Clatsop Spit. Practically nothing is known concerning this wreck.
Disappeared with its two-man crew off Willapa Bay in calm weather.

Stranded at Leadbetter Point near Willapa Bay on Jan. 4, 1885. No lives were lost in the wreck, but the ship was a total loss. It was carried ashore by the currents in a thick fog, command by Captain William Ross.
The schooner was driven into the south jetty of the Columbia River on Jan. 13, 1912. The crew was rescued but the vessel drifted across the river mouth and capsized, becoming a total loss.
The steamship was stranded near Peacock Spit. All passengers were rescued, but the ship was a total loss.
Wrecked in gale one mile north of Ocean Park. The ship was a total loss.
British ship stranded on Sand Island in May. No lives were lost and the vessel was later refloated, repaired and returned to service.

The vessel wrecked near Ocean Park, Wash. on Sept. 19, 1924. The craft was wrecked while trying to land an illegal cargo of liquor on Klipsan Beach. The crew narrowly escaped with their lives, and the vessel was leveled by the surf.

The ship was stranded in heavy weather at dusk. All passengers were rescued the following morning. Several weeks later, the vessel was safely refloated after having been considered a total loss. The stranding was attributed to the vessel getting out of the marked channel.

The schooner and 11 crew members went missing after clearing the Columbia Bar on Feb. 28, 1918. It was believed to have foundered in a gale, but no trace was ever found. The 204-foot ship was carrying lumber from Astoria to Sydney, Australia.
Vanished with all hands several miles west of the Columbia Bar on Dec. 11, 1900. It is believed to have foundered in a gale off the Washington Coast on December 15, but no trace has ever been found.

Vanished at sea with a party of seven men in January, 1869. The vessel was outbound from Oysterville with a cargo of oysters for San Francisco. Some speculated that the schooner had carried additional sail for a fast passage south, due to the perisable cargo, perhaps causing it to capsize and sink.

Stranded on Clatsop Spit on March 28, 1875. As it followed the ship Pactolus across the bar, the wind failed, causing it to run aground on the sands. Captain Mertage and his crew were rescued by a lifeboat that was towed to the scene by the tug Astoria.

Wrecked on Clatsop Spit in 1886. The crew is believed to have been saved. No record appears to have been kept as to which schooner Ariel was lost at the river mouth, claimed to have two different ships.
Wrecked at Cranberry Road, a few miles north of Long Beach, on February 13,1947.
The tugboat exploded and burned off Astoria on Jan. 21, 1949, killing one.
Wrecked south of Klipsan Beach in 1889. The vessel was one of the early-day units of the Shoalwater Bay mosquito fleet.
Stranded on the Columbia Bar in August, 1911. The vessel was later refloated and repaired.
Stranded on the sands off Grays Bay in June, 1849. The 26 passengers aboard were all rescued. A short while after the rescue, a gale arose and destroyed the vessel. All hands were saved.

Stranded on April 29, 1925, off Cape Shoalwater at the entrance to Willapa Harbor. With great effort the vessel was finally refloated but was so badly damaged that it was never put back into service, and was scrapped instead.
Stranded at the Columbia River entrance on March 1, but was later refloated.
The ship ran aground on Clatsop Spit after breaking loose from tug Sea Lion on Nov. 24, carrying 16,600 tons of petroleum. A salvage tug pulled it free two days later.
Stranded at the mouth of the Columbia River, May 14. It was later refloated.

The unnamed oil barge was carried up on the beach north of Long Beach after being cut loose from the tug Tidewater Shaver off Columbia Bar. The 100-foot barger was being towed to Portland from Honolulu.
Wrecked on Clatsop Spit on August 3, 1940.
The crab trawler foundered on August 19, 1960 off Cape Disappointment.

Wrecked on Clatsop Spit on Dec. 13. The brig ran into the Columbia River for an unscheduled call and fell victim to the currents when the wind died on the bar. The crew walked ashore on dry sand, but the vessel was later demolished in the surf.
Disappeared with all hands after departing the Columbia River in December. It is believed to have foundered in a gale.

The freighter struck bottom and began leaking while outbound over Willapa Bar because of steering troubles. After the crew was removed, the ship was towed across the Columbia River bar by a tug boat and continued leaking. Eventually, the ship settled lower in the water and became a total loss.
Drifted ashore bottom up on North Beach Peninsula on March 26.

Pounded unmercifully by heavy seas while crossing the Columbia River Bar on Jan. 4, the damaged ship drifted northward at the mercy of the elements and was lost with the entire crew. The ship later drifted as far as the British Columbia coast.
Stranded on Sand Island.
Stranded on Clatsop Spit on Sept. 26. All hands were rescued, but the vessel was a total loss.
The steamship got stranded in the fog on Willapa Bar and eventually broke in two.
Wrecked north of Ocean Park on Feb. 5. The crew abandoned the schooner at sea.
The ship vanished off the mouth of the Columbia River with a crew of 15. It is believed to have been a victim of a terrific storm.
Stranded in a gale four miles east of the Fort Canby Lifesaving Station on December 21. In all, 47 passengers were rescued.
Stranded near the present location of Long Beach on Jan. 3. The wrecked killed three people, while two others struggled ashore in the surf.
Exploded and sank off Tongue Point.

Stranded on the sands two miles south of the Cape Disappointment Light. The vessel had been at anchor on the bar awaiting favorable winds when a strong breeze came up suddenly from the south and swept it ashore with anchors dragging. A rescue crew saved 16 men and the captain.
Caught fire off the Oregon Coast and burned for several days until towed across Willapa bar and scuttled in the Willapa River.

The ship was dismasted and waterlogged off Shoalwater Bay. The crew took to boats and were later picked up at sea. The wreck capsized and became a menace to navigation, and was later rammed and sunk by the steamship Pacific.
Stranded on what is now part of Peacock Spit. Though the stranding was at first believed to be of a serious nature they got the ship off on the change of the tide.
The ship grounded on the southwest end of Peacock Spit. Four lives were lost, but the freighter was pulled to safety in one of the most remarkable salvage feats of the decade.

Wrecked on Clatsop Spit after the currents carried the ship onto the shoal when the wind failed on the bar. The anchor cables parted and the vessel was dashed hard on the sands. The crew made shore safely.
Burned to the water's edge on Feb. 10. The vessel was built in 1909 and was a veteran fishboat in the area.

Carried ashore inside McKenzie Head at the north entrance of the Columbia River. The crew was saved, and several months later the vessel was refloated in one of the most interesting salvage feats ever performed.

Foundered twelve miles southwest of the Columbia Bar, carrying a full cargo of grain. A heavy swell caused it to strike the sands and take on water. At midnight the vessel had taken ten feet of water and the pumps were choked with wheat chaff. Finally it was abandoned and the crew was rescued.
Stranded on Clatsop Spit on July 15, but was later salvaged and repaired.
Driven ashore four miles south of Ocean Park on May 15, 1950, when the main water pump failed. The schooner was salvaged and towed to safety.
Stranded on Desdemona Sands, so named after the wreck, which resulted in one death.
Burned, a quarter mile up the entrance to the North River.

Stranded on the sands of the Columbia Bar on Christmas. In 20 minutes, seven feet of water filled the hold, and the frightened crew refused to work. The brig's master lashed the wheel hard over and squared the sails, then gave the order to abandon ship. The men were picked up by the pilot boat California and taken to Astoria in time for Christmas dinner.
Wrecked on Clatsop Spit in 1884. Very little is known concerning this wreck, but the vessel is said by some to have been an early British tramp steamer.

Went aground in the fog near Leadbetter Point. Overrunning the Columbia entrance, the ship was trapped by the currents and carried northward. Despite dropping both anchors, the vessel dragged on to the beach and became a total loss. A rescue crew got a line on the wreck and rescued the thirteen men aboard.

Met disaster while carrying a full grain cargo. While sailing, the ship veered toward shore and ran aground on the tip of Peacock Spit. Rescue boats tried in vain to pull it to safety, but under a heavy load the ship refused to oblige. The crew abandoned and made a narrow escape in the boats.
Wrecked on the Clatsop Spit while attempting to enter the river. The vessel was carried onto the beach and demolished, but the crew reached shore safely.
The shipwreck killed three crew members near Ocean Park. The wreck was removed from the beach via the overland route.
Was discovered, bottom up, several miles off the mouth of the Columbia River. No trace of the crew has ever been found.
Wrecked on Clatsop Beach killing all seven aboard. Also referred to as "Unknown Sloop of 1876."
Foundered outside the Columbia River entrance. The crew of 49 were all rescued.
Went missing with all hands en route to Manila from Astoria. The iron vessel was last seen crossing the Columbia Bar well freighted with a load of lumber.
The gas-powered fishing boat foundered near Tillamook Rock.

Stranded on the sands of the Columbia bar, carrying a cargo of wheat. As it yawed on the sands, the ship's stempost cracked and the rudder was unshipped as the vessel began to break up. The Fort Canby surfboat crew arrived on the scene and rescued the ship's company.
The gas-propelled ship burned three miles above the mouth of the North River.
Carried ashore near Seaview, just north of North Head, after becoming waterlogged at sea.

Destroyed by a fire caused by a fuel tank explosion after departing Ilwaco, Wash. The captain and crew of 10 took to the boat and were picked up, half-clothed, by the motor lifeboat from Cape Disappointment.
Lost on the Columbia Bar. No lives were lost.

Stranded on the Clatsop Spit. All hands were rescued. A Coast Guard cutter attempted several times to pull the boat to safety, but was unsuccessful. A year later only its mast remained above the sand and surf.
The vessel was loaded with lumber when it wrecked on Shoalwater Bar and was destroyed. The crew was saved after a narrow escape in the surf.
Collided with buoy No. 12 near the entrance to the Columbia Bar and was lost.

properties.ship_name: J. C. Cousins, Am. pilot schr.
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: Stranded on Clatsop Spit. No trace of the four-person was ever found.
Loaded with 2,100 tons of coal, the ship ran ashore and broke apart. The captain, his wife and seven crewmen survived, but eight died. Remains are occasionally seen after storms.

Stranded on Clatsop Spit, the ship was given up as a total loss and abandoned by its crew, who were picked up by the tug Columbia. Later the schooner drifted off the shoal and floated out to sea where it was picked up comparatively undamaged by the tug Columbia.
Stranded on the Shoalwater Bar, outbound to San Francisco carrying oysters. The crew struggled to safety through the surf.
Some old accounts say a vessel of this name was wrecked at the entrance to the Columbia River in July, 1858, but this cannot be confirmed.
No notes from Gibbs.

The ship was dismasted and waterlogged off Shoalwater Bay. The crew took to lifeboats and were later picked up at sea. The wreck capsized and became a menace to navigation, and was later rammed and sunk by the steamship Pacific.

Cast ashore on Clatsop Spit when the captain mistook Tillamook Rock Light for Point Adams Light, and ran his ship onto the beach. A steamer attempted to rescue the crew, but was prevented from getting near the wreck by the heavy surf. The crew managed to launch a damaged lifeboat and row to safety.

Wrecked near Tansy Point while towing logs at the mouth of the Columbia, klilling four people. The captain refused to cut his tow loose, expecting to get off on the next tide, but the mounting surf carried the log raft ashore and pulled the tug after it, causing it to capsize and sink. One man cut the log raft free and rode it to safety. Another clung to the mast until a rescue party arrived.
Between 15 and 20 people died as a furious storm struck the fishing fleet, with winds exceeding 100 mph. Numerous fishermen were rescued by other vessels in the area.
Lost near the Columbia River jetty, killing two.
After parting its hawser while under tow, the vessel drifted ashore near Tillamook Head where it was dashed to pieces.

The steamship foundered in a gale 60 miles southwest of the Columbia River. Out of 67 people, only two were saved. The ship was carrying railroad ties, which later landed on Tillamook and Nehalem beaches, along with some bodies.

Stranded at Leadbetter Point just south of the entrance to Willapa Bay, striking the beach at night in thick weather. The captain ordered the masts chopped down in an effort to lighten the vessel to no avail, and the crew of 16 had to be rescued.

Stranded on Clatsop Beach at night while inbound from Junin, Chile. While waiting in severe weather for a pilot into the Columbia River, the ship got in too close to shore and was carried onto the beach by the surf. A few years later the ship was devoured by the sands.
Damaged severely and structurally disabled on the Columbia River Bar.
Stranded on Clatsop Spit. At first it was feared the ship would be lost, but a determined salvage effort eventually refloated it from the sand.

properties.ship_name: Gen. C. H. Muir, U.S.N. trans
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: Suddenly sank at dockside, while berthed at Astoria. Shallow water kept the ship from going down beyond its superstructure. It was hastily patched and pumped out, temporarily repaired, and later dry-docked at Portland.

The dredge ran aground on the north jetty of the Columbia River while working in the area. The ship remained hung up on the rocks for a terrifying 20 minutes. The captain freed the vessel, but sharp jetty rocks had punched a sizable hole in the port side, and it was taking water into the hull. After nine days the mammoth dredge was back at work.
The steamship ran aground on Clatsop Spit and began sinking, killing 42 people aboard. Some two years later, the whole stern frame of the vessel was found on the beach 60 miles north of the wreck.

The lumber barge broke loose from a tug while crossing the Columbia River Bar with a load of lumber. Coast Guard vessels began to tow the vessel in rough waters toward Astoria, but the damaged barge began sinking. To prevent it from sinking in the channel, the boats ran it aground off Cape Disappointment.

Capsized off Tongue Point after a gale swept the lower river. The cargo shifted and the craft heeled over, drowning three passengers. The remaining 27 passengers took refuge in a fishing boat that the steamer was towing.
Stranded north of Ocean Park, killing two people.
Ran aground on the south jetty of the Columbia River, punching holes in the hull. The crew of six waded ashore safely.
Lost at Willapa Harbor on Christmas Day, 1908.
Wrecked at North Head. The crew was saved but the vessel was a total loss.

The vessel was traveling along coast in a thick fog near Leadbetter Point when it drifted into the breakers, knocking several holes in the hull and forcing the crew to take to the boats. Parts of the barnacle-encrusted remains could be seen on the peninsula as late as 1964.
The passanger steamer got stranded on Sand Island. All passengers were safely evacuated, but 11 crew members drowned in the last full lifeboat to leave the wreck.
Sranded four miles north of North Head. The vessel was beyond salvage.
The chief officer and four crewmen died in a small boat while trying to determine the Columbia Bar depths.
Omitted from records, it is said to have been a French ship that stranded on the south side of the Columbia river entrance in 1860.

Grounded on a reef of rocks in a gale, just above Astoria on the south side of the Columbia River. The ship settled on both anchors, which forced a hole in the bottom and caused it to sink. The iron vessel was salvaged and used as a barge, converted into a steamer and eventually a four-masted schooner.
Struck bottom and went down off Cape Disappointment. The crew of three swam to safety.
Stranded on the middle sands at the Columbia River mouth, killing 17 people.

Carried up on the beach and abandoned, just north of Long Beach, after it and a smaller oil barge were cut loose from a tug and carried by the prevailing currents and breakers to Peninsula beach. The barges were cut loose when they threatened to carry the tug onto treacherous Peacock Spit.
Stranded and foundered off Peacock Spit, killing the entire crew of 34.
The unknown Japanese vessel drifted ashore on Clatsop Spit after being carried across the Pacific Ocean with the prevailing current.
The unkown Japanese vessel washed up in pieces along the North Beach Peninsula. Though the craft was not identified, it undoubtedly drifted across the Pacific with the strong Japanese current.

Wrecked on a rocky shelf off North Head. The ship immediately began to break up, and the crew experienced difficulty in launching a boat. One passenger was swept overboard and drowned. After several hours in an open boat, the ship's party landed on North Beach, exhausted from their tribulations.
Wrecked at the entrance to Shoalwater Bay.
Very little is known of this wreck except that the vessel was totally destroyed as it wrecked on Clatsop Spit. Some sources claimed it was of British registry, others French registry.
Foundered off Willapa Bay killing the crew of four.
Swept onto the spit near the south jetty of the Columbia River. The craft was destroyed in the surf but the crew was rescued.

Unable to get a pilot, the ship attempted to cross the Columbia Bar unaided. It struck the shoals, badly damaging the keel and destroying the rudder. It later came off the reef and drifted into Baker Bay, where it was rescured. A box rudder was constructed and the crews of several vessels helped pump and bail, so the ship could continue upriver to Portland.

Stranded at Leadbetter Point when the captain mistook Shoalwater Bar for the Columbia Bar. A lifesaving crew picked up the survivors, while beachcombers picked up its cargo of coal to heat their homes.
Stranded on Peacock Spit, killing one.
Stranded near Ocean Park.
Came ashore on Clatsop Spit, bottom up. The crew of nine was never found.
Grounded on Clatsop Spit at the Columbia River entrance, six or seven miles from Astoria.
Foundered six miles west of the Columbia River Lightship.
The sailing vessel struck the shore and foundered off Tillamook Head. All 16 crew members died. A dog was the only survivor.
Capsized off the Columbia River Bar.
Disappeared with its crew of nine off the mouth of the Coulmbia River. Shortly after it departed, a terrible gale roared across the the Columbia River mouth.

Wrecked on Clatsop Spit. The ship's master elected to cross the Columbia Bar in a small boat when he couldn't get a pilot for his ship. The ship eventually ended up on the spit and became a total loss.
The sailing vessel was found, bottom up, off Tillamook Head. No sign of the 11 crew members was ever found.
A pleasure boat built in Michigan, the vessel burned at Warrenton.

Wrecked in a fog two miles north of Cape Disappointment, killing nine. A boat was put over the side but immediately swamped, drowning its occupants. Two survivors struggled through the surf to safety and were later found on the beach suffering from exposure.
Foundered off Peacock Spit in the summer of 1913.

Stuck fast on a spit near Tongue Point, the ship was carrying 161 men of the 1st Artillery to Fort Vancouver. The ship was freed and successfully dropped anchor at Fort Vancouver, bringing the first American troops officially stationed in Oregon Territory.
The steamship was stranded off Clatsop Beach. All hands were saved.
Partially dismasted in a storm in December. Abandoned at sea by the crew, the derelict ship was later picked up off the mouth of the Columbia River.
Wrecked along with Triumph and two U.S. Coast Gaurd motor lifeboats. All lives were lost.
Put into Astoria ablaze. The fire was finally squelched but repairs were costly. The vessel later wrecked off the west coast of Vancouver Island.
Stranded off Sand Island.
Wrecked on North Beach Peninsula, killing two.
Stranded off Sand Island, killing one.

Damaged beyond repair in heavy seas. The schooner sent out a call for help, but the Coast Guard was attending to another wreck. The ship was eventually escorted over the bar, but its condition left it no longer fit for sea duty.
Disappeared with its entire crew after crossing the Columbia Bar.
Foundered near the Columbia River Lightship, killing two.

Struck by a steamship while maneuvering to get a line on the vessel off the mouth of the Columbia River. The tug's tanks were punctured and it sank. A Coast Guard cutter picked up the survivors, but one of the tug's crew died of a heart attack in the icy waters.

Sank after colliding with a Columbia Bar buoy. After striking the buoy, the ship ran for the jetty sands to prevent it from sinking in deep water. But because a big hole had been knocked in its side, it sank before reaching the sands. The full crew of 16 was rescued.
Struck the sands of the Columbia Bar and sank 25 miles northwest of the river. The crew abandoned the ship and were picked up by sailing vessels. The ship went down a few hours later.
Stranded on Clatsop Spit after breaking loose from a tug off the mouth of the Columbia River. The steel barge went ashore with 600,000 feet of peeler logs, which washed off the deck.
Stranded on the north spit of Willapa Bar.
Stranded on Peacock Spit. After 13 months, the ship refloated itself.
Smashed to bits in a storm off the Columbia River entrance. All three aboard perished.
Suffered a serious structural crack while crossing the Columbia Bar, spilling oil all the way to Portland. Oil damage to the fishing industry was heavy.
Stranded on Sand Island, and abandoned by the captain and crew. Salavgers later boarded the vessel and after herculean efforts succeeded in getting it afloat.
Lost on the Columbia Bar in the fall of 1914.
Wrecked at the south entrance to Willapa Bay near Leadbetter Point.
Destroyed on the south sands inside Clatsop Spit.

Struck bottom off the south jetty of the Columbia Bar, killing six. After running into a strong gale, the freshwater tanks became filled with sea water, prompting the captain to reverse course. The vessel was tossed ashore on the bar and capsized. The lone survivor struggled up on the jetty rocks and was found by the lifesaving crew blue with cold.

Parted its towing line and went aground on the North Beach Peninsula, laden with 700 tons of explosives. After several failed attempts, it was eventually freed using a light plane to fly lines to the barge while 600 spectators along the beach looked on.

properties.ship_name: P.S. B. & D. Co. No. 14, Am. scow
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: The scow was built in 1913 and owned by the Puget Sound Bridge and Dredging Company.

properties.ship_name: P. T. & B Co. 1685, Am. barge
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: The American barges were being towed to Honolulu, each loaded with lumber. Off the mouth of the Columbia River, heavy seas and high winds carried the tug and barges toward Peacock Spit. The surf made kindling of the cargo and the barges were a total loss. One of the barges was swept against the rock walls of North Head.

properties.ship_name: P. T. & B. Co. 1684, Am. barge
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: The American barges were being towed to Honolulu, each loaded with lumber. Off the mouth of the Columbia River, heavy seas and high winds carried the tug and barges toward Peacock Spit. The surf made kindling of the cargo and the barges were a total loss. One of the barges was swept against the rock walls of North Head.

Stranded on Leadbetter Point at the south entrance to Shoalwater Bay as it attempted to enter the bay in a thick fog. When the crew and passengers were abandoning the ship, the captain was swept overboard and drowned. The others reached shore safely, but the vessel was pounded to pieces.
Lost at the mouth of the Columbia River.
Burned at Astoria.
The dory from the Peacock drifted 40 miles from the Columbia Bar, resulting in the loss of one life.
Stranded on Peacock Spit.

The charter fishing vessel radioed for help when a fuel line clogged and the vessel began leaking. Two rescue vessels took the fishing boat in tow, but the Pearl heeled over and began to sink. Two people were rescued and eight others went missing. It was the worst charter fishing boat disaster in the Columbia River area, and an extensive investigation followed calling for stiff regulations.
Sustained serious damage while crossing the Columbia Bar. The steam ship was struck by huge swells and sustained serious damage.
Carried into the north jetty and demolished, killing its master.
Stranded on Peacock Spit while on a surveying mission in 1839, but eventually refloated. The spot where it grounded was for many years known as Sulphur Spit.

Went ashore in heavy weather on Clatsop Spit south of the Columbia River. The captain and crew were rescued, and the wreck landed on the beach, where it was dismantled for scrap. The forward section of the hull, with bowsprit intact, has remained a picturesque landmark at what is now Fort Stevens State Park.
Wrecked on the south jetty of the Columbia River Bar.

When cargo shifted in rough seas, the ship went over on its beam ends. The crew abandoned ship and were rescued. The ship was towed into Astoria, repaired and sent back to sea, much to the suprise of the crew. It was later destroyed in World War I.

After being struck by a gale the day earlier, the schooner's engines broke down and water leaked into the hull, extinguishing the fires in the boilers. Wind and high seas carried the ship to shore, where rescue crews helped save all 17 aboard. The vessel was pounded to pieces.
Stranded north of Shoalwater Bar and eventually refloated.

Wrecked on the Columbia Bar, carrying lumber. The cargo was jettisoned after the vessel struck and bumped the shoals for several hours. It finally drifted free and was carried to Astoria with the tide and currents, where is was pronounced a total loss.
Stranded on North Beach Peninsula near Long Beach.
Encounted a severe storm off the mouth of the Columbia River and plunged to the bottom with all hands on New Year's Day, January 1, 1900.

properties.ship_name: Queen of the Pacific, Am. S.5
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: The passenger ship was stranded on Clatsop Spit, and refloated using a fleet of tugs.
The British sloop of war was stranded briefly on the Columbia River bar while inbound to Astor Colony (Fort George) in 1813.
Stranded off the main channel near Tongue Point, and later refloated.
Came ashore on Clatsop Beach, bottom up, and is believed to have capsized off the mouth of the Columbia River. No trace of the crew of four has ever been found.
Burned at Warrenton.
Foundered off the mouth of the Columbia River, killing its crew of four. Part of the bow and forward deck drifted ashore on North Beach Peninsula several months later.
Said to have been wrecked off North Head.
Dragged anchor and was smashed against the rocks of the north jetty of the Columbia Bar in a storm. The skipper and his crew fortunately escaped death.

Stranded on Peacock Spit. A tug tried, but failed to pull the ship free, forcing the crew to flee in the boats for the beach. The vessel was regarded as a veritable floating coffin, its hull being old and tender, and was a total loss.

Burned to the water's edge by a mutinous crew on Shoalwater Bay. The crew quarreled while loading a cargo of oysters and set the ship on fire. Then, unable to get away, the crew became permanent settlers near what has since been known as Bruceport, for the name of the ship. In another version of the story, the ship's cook is said to have gone mad, set the ship on fire, and disappeared.
The vessel drifted ashore, bottom up, on North Beach Peninsula. No trace of the crew of 25 was ever found.

After having been buffeted by a storm that killed 11 crew members off Yaquina Head, the ship was rebuilt into a rock barge and later a passenger seam schooner. The steamer struck Clatsop Spit at night in thick weather. The crew was rescued but the breakers caused the cargo of coal to catch on fire and the wreck became a torch. By morning it was on the bottom with only a few charred timbers breaking the surface.
Disappeared with a crew of four somewhere off the mouth of the Columbia River.
Went aground on the south spit of Shoalwater bar.

Plunged to the bottom off Peacock Spit killing 33. In a gale, the captain lost his bearings and let his ship overrun the channel entrance, coming head-on with the tip of Peacock Spit. The ship broke in two and the crew was forced onto the rigging. One by one they were swept into the water. Only three survived, clinging to the mast.
Stranded on Peacock Spit.
Stranded on Clatsop Spit, going hard aground. The crew took to the boats and survived. The brig eventually fell to pieces.
Stranded at Youngs Bay near Astoria and later pulled free.

Went ashore near Long Beach after breaking away from a tug during a heavy gale. The tug returned a week later and succeeded in pulling the barge off the beach. The salvage job was considered "remarkable" as most of the jobs of this kind have proved unsuccessful.

Capsized and sank in 18-foot swells while in tow by a Coast Guard rescue boat. While six people were rescued, two of the crew and one Coast Guardsman died in the incident. Poor communication and a failure to evacuate the vessel were blamed for the deaths.
Stranded on the Columbia Bar.
Wrecked on Clatsop Spit and was a total loss.
Stranded near the south jetty of the Columbia River. The vessel was built the previous year.
Stranded on Clatsop Spit and was a total loss.
Stranded near Sand Island and was later salvaged and returned to sea.
Foundered off Peacock Spit.

properties.ship_name2: Silvie de Grace or Sylvia de Grasse
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: Wrecked on rock ledge near Astoria, and was a total loss.
Stranded north of Ocean Park.
Stranded on Clatsop Beach, supposedly in the year 1725, years before white explorers discovered the mouth of the Columbia River.

properties.ship_name: State of Washington, Am. Riv. Str
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: Destroyed by terrific explosion off Tongue Point. The steamer was towing an oil barge when a boiler exploded, killing one and seriously injuring six others. The sternwheeler was so completely demolished that all that kept the wreck afloat was the hawser that remained fast to the oil barge. The injured men were rescued.
Wrecked south of Ocean Park, killing seven.
Ran aground on Peacock Spit in a snowstorm, after its tiller cable broke. The crew members waded ashore.
Caught fire and was beached north of Astoria, killing one.

Stranded momentarily on the Columbia Bar. Because of the captain's haste to cross the bar before a heavy sea had abated, he sent several of his men needlessly out to sound the bar in small boats; eight of them drowned.

properties.type_of_ship: Coast Guard motor lifeboats CG-40564 (40-footer) and CG-36454 (36-footer), and crab boat Mermaid
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: Stranded momentarily on the Columbia Bar. Because of the captain's haste to cross the bar before a heavy sea had abated, he sent several of his men needlessly out to sound the bar in small boats; eight of them drowned.

Foundered off Peacock Spit as the captain and two crew members were returning from a fishing trip. High seas hit the boat, sinking it in an hour. The captain burned a bucket of gasoline to attract the attention of a rescue boat, which picked the men up.
Stranded on the north spit of Willapa Bar, killing one.
This boat, along with Mermaid and two Coast Guard motor lifeboats were all lost on the Columbia Bar, killing seven people between all four vessels.
Broke loose from its moorings and was totally wrecked after grounding on Sand Island.

Wrecked on the middle sands of the Columbia Bar. Pilot S. C. Reeves, the first officially appointed bar pilot in the lower Columbia, assured the captain that he could make the crossing with his eyes closed, but the vessel drifted in strong currents and hung up on the bar. All hands abandoned the ship and managed to reach shore. Among the cargo was much finery and clothing that was salvaged by the Clatsop people.
Washed ashore north of Cape Disappointment, killing nine.
Stranded on Peacock Spit.
No notes from Gibbs.

Wrecked on Peacock Spit, loaded with rails for the Northern Pacific Railroad. Hundreds of people gathered to watch as the rescue crews paced the beach below. The crew of 18 finally managed to escape the wreck in the boats, but experienced a rugged ordeal before they reached the beach.

properties.ship_name: W. T. & B. No.3, Am. Barge
properties.detailed_notes_by_gibbs: Lost at the entrance to the Columbia River.
No notes from Gibbs.
Stranded on Peacock Spit, and removed in a daring rescue attempt.
Dragged anchor and drifted against the south jetty of the Columbia River while being towed from Fort Stevens to Astoria. The barge was finally pulled off with a kedge anchor.

Dragged anchors and was carried aground on Desdemona Sands at the mouth of the Columbia River. Ater being hung up on the spit for a considerable time, tugs succeeded in getting it off, taking it to Young's Bay for repairs.

Abandoned by its crew off Tillamook Rock Light after being buffeted by a severe gale. The crew reached shore safely while the vessel, completely waterlogged, was towed into the Columbia and dismantled.

Sank inside the mouth of the Columbia River. Caught in a gale off Tillamook Rock and beginning to leak, the schooner made it to Hammond where it sank in 20 feet of water. Months later it was raised and repaired.
Collided with the American freighter Iowan, killing seven.

Wrecked on North Beach Peninsula, in thick weather and strong currents, which caused the vessel to overrun the river entrance and go ashore on the sands of the peninsula. The captain said his unfamiliarity with the coastline and the natural forces of the area were responsible for the wreck.

Stranded on Clatsop Beach, but was saved from destruction by a Coast Guard cutter that braved shallow waters and got a line on the lumber freighter. The vessel stranded after dragging its anchors with a jammed rudder.
Wrecked at the Willapa Bay entrance in 1861, killing two of the crew as they attempted to reach shore.

Wrecked on Clatsop Spit with an estimated loss of 26 to 46 lives. Rescuers attempted to save those on the vessel but became too exhausted in their battle against the sea and were forced to abandon their effort. The ship was pounded by the sea through the night killing alll aboard.

Dismasted and waterlogged in a gale off the Columbia River. The crew was rescued, and later the derelict ship was found and towed to Astoria as a prize, where it underwent extensive repairs and returned to the sea.

The ship was caught in a gale off the mouth of the Columbia River and tugged as far as Sand Island, where hurricane-force winds blew the ship onto the shoal. The three masts were cut away, which allowed it to drift free. It was repaired, but four years later it wrecked for good on Puget Sound.

Stranded on Clatsop Spit. All cargo, including 104 head of cattle, were thrown overboard to lighten the load, but the vessel had been punctured and started taking water. The crew was forced to man the boats and were rescued. Only one cow reached shore alive, though for years she was accused of having salt water in her milk.

Stranded on Leadbetter Point, just south of the Willapa Bay entrance. The schooner was caught in a gale off the Columbia River and lost its rudder. It drifted at the mercy of the wind and was ground on the sands. The crew was all saved, and the schooner was eventually refloated and towed to port for repairs.
The barge broke loose from a tugboat towline in bad weather on the Columbia Bar.
